# docplaybook

`docplaybook` is a local-first CLI for Markdown documentation translation.

It watches a workspace, groups files into doc sets, incrementally updates translated files when the source changes, and learns reusable translation guidance from human edits. The long-term goal is to keep the core engine provider-agnostic so the same sync and memory workflow can work for local files today and cloud documents later.

## Why Memory Matters

Most translation automation tools can generate a decent first draft. The real pain starts after humans review and improve that draft:

- a reviewer fixes a product term once, but the next translation pass makes the same mistake again
- a carefully polished paragraph gets partially retransmitted and loses the reviewer’s preferred wording
- the same correction has to be repeated across many documents because the tool never turned it into reusable project knowledge
- a new teammate joins the docs workflow and has no durable record of past translation decisions
- a term is corrected in one page, but the rest of the doc site still contains the old term

This project is built around the idea that human corrections should not be treated as one-off edits. They should become tracked translation memory for the whole project.

## Painful Examples

### 1. Terminology Drift

Source:

```md
飞书知识库支持权限控制。
```

A model translates `知识库` as `Knowledge Base`, but the team wants `Wiki` because that is the actual product name.

Someone fixes it by hand. A week later the source sentence changes slightly, the file is retransmitted, and the tool writes `Knowledge Base` again.

That is exactly the kind of repeated regression this project is trying to avoid.

### 2. Review Work Gets Lost

A translated page is already reviewed and polished by a human. Then the source page changes in one paragraph. A naive sync tool often rewrites too much of the target page, which can wipe out hard-won improvements in nearby text.

Block-level sync helps reduce that blast radius. Memory helps keep the corrected style and terminology alive in future translations.

### 3. The Same Fix Repeated Across The Site

Suppose one reviewer changes:

- `租户` from `tenant account` to `tenant`
- `知识库` from `knowledge base` to `wiki`
- `空间` from `workspace` to `space`

Without tracked memory, reviewers may need to make the same three fixes in dozens of files. Once those decisions are captured in the project playbook, every future translation can inherit them.

### 4. Project Knowledge Lives In People’s Heads

In many docs teams, the real translation rules are not written anywhere:

- which terms must stay untranslated
- which product names have official English forms
- whether the tone should be concise or explanatory
- whether API field names should be mirrored literally or kept in English

When that knowledge is only in reviewers’ heads, quality depends on who happens to review the file. A tracked memory file turns those decisions into project assets.

### 5. A New Correction Should Be Reusable Beyond One File

If a new translation rule is discovered in one document, it should not stay trapped there. The long-term direction for this tool is that a newly learned memory can be applied and revalidated across the rest of the workspace, especially for terminology corrections and other highly reusable fixes.

## What It Does

- Watches a workspace instead of a single file.
- Groups multiple documents into multiple doc sets.
- Supports sibling-file layout first: `guide.md`, `guide.en.md`, `guide.ja.md`.
- Splits Markdown into blocks and only retranslates changed translatable blocks.
- Preserves non-translatable blocks such as frontmatter, code fences, HTML blocks, and thematic breaks.
- Learns from human edits by updating a project-level translation playbook for each language pair.
- Stores runnable state outside the repository so snapshots and hashes do not pollute the workspace.

## Architecture

The first implementation is deliberately split into layers:

- `DocumentProvider`: where documents come from. The first provider is local files.
- `LayoutAdapter`: how files map into a logical doc set. The first preset is `sibling`.
- `TranslationEngine`: block-level translation using the Vercel AI SDK.
- `MemoryEngine`: updates a plain-text translation playbook from human corrections.
- `RuntimeStore`: stores snapshots, hashes, and previous generated baselines outside the repository.

Internally the CLI works with:

- `Workspace`: one root folder passed to `docplaybook <path>`.
- `DocSet`: one source document plus its translated variants.
- `DocumentRef`: one concrete file in one language.

## Why Runtime State Lives Outside The Repo

The core sync loop needs more than Git history:

- source snapshot from the last processed run
- previous generated translation snapshot
- current on-disk translation snapshot

That lets the agent answer two different questions:

- what changed in the source since the last processed baseline
- what the human changed in the translation relative to the last generated baseline

Those baselines are operational state, not product content, so they are stored in the user data directory:

- macOS: `~/Library/Application Support/docplaybook/workspaces/<workspace-id>/`
- Linux: `$XDG_STATE_HOME/docplaybook/workspaces/<workspace-id>/`
- Windows: `%LOCALAPPDATA%/docplaybook/workspaces/<workspace-id>/`

You can override the root with `DOCPLAYBOOK_HOME`.

## Config

Project config and tracked memories live inside the workspace:

```text
<workspace>/
  docplaybook/
    config.json
    memories/
      zh-CN__en.md
      zh-CN__ja.md
```

Recommended model config shape:

- `gateway`: use Vercel AI Gateway and pass a gateway model string such as `openai/gpt-5-mini`
- `openai`: call OpenAI directly with the official provider package
- `anthropic`: call Anthropic directly with the official provider package
- `openai-compatible`: use a user-specified OpenAI-compatible endpoint such as OpenRouter or a self-hosted gateway

Example `docplaybook/config.json` using Vercel AI Gateway:

```json
{
  "version": 1,
  "provider": {
    "kind": "local"
  },
  "sourceLanguage": "zh-CN",
  "targetLanguages": ["en", "ja"],
  "layout": {
    "kind": "sibling"
  },
  "model": {
    "kind": "gateway",
    "model": "openai/gpt-5-mini",
    "apiKeyEnv": "AI_GATEWAY_API_KEY"
  },
  "watch": {
    "ignore": ["**/node_modules/**", "**/.git/**", "**/dist/**", "**/docplaybook/**"]
  }
}
```

The model block is intentionally user-controlled. API keys are never stored in the repo:

- `gateway` mode uses the AI SDK Gateway model string and reads the API key from an env var.
- `openai` mode uses the official OpenAI provider package and reads the API key from an env var.
- `anthropic` mode uses the official Anthropic provider package and reads either an API key or auth token from env vars.
- `openai-compatible` mode lets you point at any OpenAI-compatible endpoint using env vars for both the base URL and API key.

Example `openai` config:

```json
{
  "kind": "openai",
  "model": "gpt-5-mini",
  "apiKeyEnv": "OPENAI_API_KEY",
  "baseUrlEnv": "OPENAI_BASE_URL"
}
```

Example `anthropic` config:

```json
{
  "kind": "anthropic",
  "model": "claude-sonnet-4-5",
  "apiKeyEnv": "ANTHROPIC_API_KEY",
  "authTokenEnv": "ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN",
  "baseUrlEnv": "ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL"
}
```

Example `openai-compatible` config:

```json
{
  "kind": "openai-compatible",
  "providerName": "openrouter",
  "model": "google/gemini-2.5-flash",
  "baseUrlEnv": "OPENROUTER_BASE_URL",
  "apiKeyEnv": "OPENROUTER_API_KEY"
}
```

`docplaybook` also auto-loads env files from the workspace root before it creates the model client:

- `.env`
- `.env.local`
- `.env.docplaybook`
- `.env.docplaybook.local`

Recommended practice:

- commit `docplaybook/config.json`
- keep secrets in `.env.local` or `.env.docplaybook.local`
- use shell env vars or CI secrets in automation environments

## Translation Memory

Each language pair has one tracked Markdown playbook, for example:

- `docplaybook/memories/zh-CN__en.md`

That file is injected into every translation prompt. It behaves like a project-level translation skill or system context:

- terminology rules
- preferred phrasing
- style corrections
- reusable human overrides

That project-level memory is the main difference between this tool and a simple "translate changed files" script. The first draft matters, but preserving and reusing human corrections matters more over time.

When a human edits a translated document, the agent compares:

- previous source snapshot
- previous generated translation snapshot
- current translated file

Then it asks the LLM to update the whole playbook in place, keeping it concise and deduplicated. If the translated file was heavily restructured, the agent warns and skips memory generation for safety.

## Layout Presets

The first implemented preset is:

- `sibling`: `guide.md`, `guide.en.md`, `guide.ja.md`

The internal model is already shaped for future presets:

- `docusaurus`
- `rspress`

Those two are intentionally left as future adapters. The engine already treats documents as discrete files grouped into doc sets, which matches docs-as-code sites better than a one-file-only model.

## Installation

Project-level install for local development:

```bash
npm install
```

Run from the repo without global install:

```bash
npm run dev -- --help
```

Global install from the local repo:

```bash
npm install
npm run build
npm link
```

Then use it anywhere:

```bash
docplaybook --help
docplaybook init ./my-docs
docplaybook ./my-docs
```

Global install from a packed tarball:

```bash
npm pack
npm install -g ./docplaybook-0.1.0.tgz
```

Remove the global link:

```bash
npm unlink -g docplaybook
```

## Commands

Build:

```bash
npm run build
```

Initialize a workspace. The recommended first run is the interactive flow:

```bash
npm run dev -- init ./examples/sample-workspace
```

It will:

- detect the source language and ask for confirmation
- prompt for comma-separated target languages such as `en,ja` if none exist yet
- guide you through choosing a model provider such as OpenAI, Anthropic, Vercel AI Gateway, or a custom OpenAI-compatible provider
- check the required environment variables before the first translation and point you to `.env.docplaybook.local` if anything is missing
- initialize the workspace and immediately run the first translation pass

If you want to add more languages later, run the same command again in the same workspace:

```bash
npm run dev -- init ./examples/sample-workspace
```

Then enter new target languages such as `fr,de`. Existing target languages stay in place and only the new ones are added.

For CI or non-interactive runs, you can still pass the values explicitly:

```bash
npm run dev -- init ./examples/sample-workspace --source zh-CN --targets en,ja
```

If you do not have an API key ready yet, `init` still writes the config first, skips the initial translation, and tells you which env vars to add next.

Initialize with direct OpenAI:

```bash
npm run dev -- init ./examples/sample-workspace --model-kind openai --model gpt-5-mini
```

Initialize with direct Anthropic:

```bash
npm run dev -- init ./examples/sample-workspace --model-kind anthropic --model claude-sonnet-4-5
```

Initialize with a custom OpenAI-compatible provider:

```bash
npm run dev -- init ./examples/sample-workspace --model-kind openai-compatible --provider-name openrouter --model google/gemini-2.5-flash --api-key-env OPENROUTER_API_KEY --base-url-env OPENROUTER_BASE_URL
```

Run once:

```bash
npm run dev -- ./examples/sample-workspace --once
```

Watch continuously:

```bash
npm run dev -- ./examples/sample-workspace
```

## Research Notes

The current shape is informed by tools that solve adjacent parts of the problem, but not the full local-first memory-learning loop:

- [Azure co-op-translator](https://github.com/Azure/co-op-translator): very close to the incremental docs translation problem. It tracks source and translation status and only processes changed content, but it does not center the workflow around a tracked plain-text memory file built from human fixes.
- [Lingo.dev CLI](https://lingo.dev/en/cli): notable for keeping a delta lock file and preserving manual overrides until the source changes. That is a strong reference for incremental sync behavior in docs repos.
- [GitLocalize](https://docs.gitlocalize.com/about.html): segment-based continuous localization for docs-as-code with translation memory and glossary support. It is close in capability, but it is a platform workflow rather than a local agent skeleton.
- [Crowdin GitHub integration](https://store.crowdin.com/github): a mature continuous localization model with translation memory, AI, and repo sync. Useful as a product reference, but heavier than the local-first CLI shape here.
- [Docusaurus i18n](https://docusaurus.io/docs/i18n/introduction): shows that translated docs are discrete localized files under a locale-aware directory layout.
- [Rspress i18n](https://rspress.rs/guide/basic/i18n): similarly reinforces the need for layout adapters because localized docs are arranged as separate files rather than one inline translation artifact.
- [Vercel AI SDK provider selection](https://ai-sdk.dev/docs/getting-started/choosing-a-provider): confirms that model choice should stay user-configurable instead of being hardcoded into the tool.

## Current Limits

- Only local-file workspaces are implemented.
- Only the `sibling` layout preset is implemented.
- Memory retrieval is intentionally simple: the full language-pair playbook is injected every time.
- Large structural edits in translated files are treated as warnings and do not produce memory updates.
- The Markdown block parser is best-effort and may still need refinement for very complex documents.

## Near-Term Direction

- add stronger block matching for edited lists, tables, and other complex Markdown shapes
- add layout adapters for Docusaurus and Rspress
- add project-wide revalidation workflows so a newly learned memory can be checked against existing translations
- add cloud document providers such as Feishu documents without changing the core translation and memory engine
